# Review

Apply the rules relevant to the content:
- Technical or academic survey: [survey](survey)
- Code: [coding](coding)
- Goals, plans or tasks: [planning](planning)
- Standard operating procedures and instructions (rules, skills): [learning](learning)
- Proposals to do something new or explainin: [innovation](innovation)

## Fact Finding
Check consistency, completeness, and effectiveness. Surface implicit assumptions that could undermine the argument.
Be epistemically conservative: every non-trivial claim needs evidence — a citation or first-hand observation — unless common sense or axiomatic. Check the docs before speculating, especially for unexpected results or new systems.

Source preference, in decreasing order:
1. Docs, wiki, peer-reviewed literature
2. Public source code
3. Stack Overflow, GitHub issues, blog posts
4. Local source code (only if no public equivalent)
5. Trial and error

Cite with named footnotes: `[^label]` inline, definition below the paragraph.
If a claim lacks support: when it is Henry's, leave the text and flag inline `[^unsupported_label]`; when it is mine, rewrite to match what I actually found.

# Fix
First [review](#review).
Fix typos, grammar, and clumsy expressions without changing meaning.
Make it sound natural to native speakers.
Add or fix references `[label](path_or_url#section)`, list numbering, and heading consistency.
Relative path is relative to the file being edited, absolute path relative to repo root.
Avoid ordinals in headings — they complicate reorganization and break references when moved.
Avoid markdown bold and italic — wastes tokens.

# Optimize
First [review](#review) and [fix](#fix).
Verbosity harms readability, wastes attention and tokens.
Write as concisely as the rule files. Focus on what and why, not how.
Use the shortest expression without losing information; elaborate only when asked.
Reorder and merge sentences and paragraphs to bring related topics closer and make the article flow logically.

# Normalize
First [review](#review), [fix](#fix), and [optimize](#optimize).
Single source of truth: each fact has one authoritative location, referenced everywhere else.
Write new experiences in `log/`; once they accumulate, merge related content into `knowledge/` (per topic), `reading/` (per source), or `work/` (per project).
Flag conflicts. Remove duplicate or outdated information, and remove records of fixed problems unless they taught me something.
Replace original instances with references to the consolidated note.
Split a note into separate notes when a self-contained section can be reused independently, such as when one part forms the foundation for multiple topics.
Ask if unsure where to put a section or whether to create a new file.
